<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-12-02T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-12-02T11:00:00-05:00" n="98" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d98">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.01/179: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-12-02T16:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">December 2,
                                        1919, 4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received December 2, 2:27
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>3481. Your 6209, November 24, 4 p.m. Information received from Foreign
                            Office and outside sources indicates that officially negotiations with
                                <persName corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinoff</persName> have so far been
                            confined entirely to the proposed exchange of prisoners. No reports have
                            been received from British representative regarding a Bolshevik peace
                            offer.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_DJW1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>